<paragraph id="3340217A40105F3BFF50F8944D2F3F13" blockId="7.[162,778,1822,1905]" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFF50F8944E443F51" box="[162,288,1822,1843]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name 
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFE5CF8944D713F51" box="[430,533,1822,1843]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">‘galantei’</emphasis>
is descriptive of the name of my husband, with whom I have shared many productive hours in the field (MAM).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40105F3BFCC8FF4F4BC03AC4" blockId="7.[826,1442,196,678]" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFCC8FF4F4C9938B8" box="[826,1021,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
Although generally a yellow species, variation occurs with dark markings on the face and sides of the thorax in some specimens, and yellow bands of hairs sometimes present on the anterior margins of abdominal tergites 3 and 4. The adult of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFCC8FED44CD13911" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[826,949,350,371]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galantei">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFCC8FED44CD13911" box="[826,949,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">C. galantei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFB71FED44A153911" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1155,1393,350,371]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oscillans">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFB71FED44A153911" box="[1155,1393,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Copestylum oscillans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFCC8FEF64B7A39F0" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[826,1054,380,402]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tapanti">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFCC8FEF64B7A39F0" box="[826,1054,380,402]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Copestylum tapanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general body patterning and colouration, and in having relatively broad triangularshaped surstyli in the male genitalia. It can be most readily distinguished from these two species by the yellow hairs at the base of the femorae. Within the larval stages of the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFBEAFD9C4B1F3A49" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1048,1147,534,555]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oscillans">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFBEAFD9C4B1F3A49" box="[1048,1147,534,555]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">oscillans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup that have an orange posterior breathing tube, the early stages of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFCC8FDD94CD13A0A" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[826,949,595,616]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galantei">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFCC8FDD94CD13A0A" box="[826,949,595,616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">C. galantei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are readily distinguished by the fine, soft setae of the vestiture on the apico-ventral surfaces of the lobes of the marginal band.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40105F3BFCC8FD344BEC3B70" blockId="7.[826,1442,702,786]" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840105F3BFCC8FD344CF13AB1" box="[826,917,702,723]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Biology:</emphasis>
Adults were reared from larvae in water tanks of epiphytic bromeliads (
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940105F3BFB68FD574A5D3A91" box="[1178,1337,733,755]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="274" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
), and are known only from 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40105F3BFBF7FD764BE03B70" box="[1029,1156,764,786]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="7" pageNumber="274">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
